[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] It’s been available across browsers since March 2023.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] The **`HTMLElement.attachInternals()`** method returns an `ElementInternals` object.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] This method allows a custom element to participate in HTML forms.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] The `ElementInternals` interface provides utilities for working with these elements in the same way you would work with any standard HTML form element, and also exposes the Accessibility Object Model to the element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] Thrown if the element is not a custom element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] Thrown if the "internals" feature was disabled as part of the element definition.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] Thrown if this method is called twice on the same element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] The following example demonstrates how to create a custom form-associated element with `HTMLElement.attachInternals`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/attachinternals] The `ElementInternals.form` property is then printed to the console to demonstrate that we have an `ElementInternals` object.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] The **`define()`** method of the `CustomElementRegistry` interface adds a definition for a custom element to the custom element registry, mapping its name to the constructor which will be used to create it.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] Object that controls how the element is defined.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] String specifying the name of a built-in element to extend.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] Used to create a customized built-in element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] Thrown if the provided name is not a valid custom element name.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] Thrown if the referenced constructor is not a constructor.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] The `define()` method adds a definition for a custom element to the custom element registry, mapping its name to the constructor which will be used to create it.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] To define an autonomous custom element, you should omit the `options` parameter.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] To define a customized built-in element, you must pass the `options` parameter with its `extends` property set to the name of the built-in element that you are extending, and this must correspond to the interface that your custom element class definition inherits from.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] For example, to customize the `<p>` element, you must pass `{extends: "p"}` to `define()`, and the class definition for your element must inherit from `HTMLParagraphElement`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] This element doesn't do anything: a real autonomous element would implement its functionality in its constructor and in the lifecycle callbacks provided by the standard.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] See Implementing a custom element in our guide to working with custom elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] This element extends the built-in `<p>` element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-define] In this minimal example the element doesn't implement any customization, so it will behave just like a normal `<p>` element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] The **`upgrade()`** method of the `CustomElementRegistry` interface upgrades all shadow-containing custom elements in a `Node` subtree, even before they are connected to the main document.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] A `Node` instance with shadow-containing descendant elements to upgrade.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] If there are no descendant elements that can be upgraded, no error is thrown.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] When an HTML element is parsed or created, it may use a tag name that corresponds to a custom element (e.g., `<my-element>`).
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] If the custom element's class has not yet been registered with the appropriate `CustomElementRegistry` at the time the element is created, the element exists as an undefined, plain `HTMLElement`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] It looks and behaves like any unknown element — it has no special behavior, lifecycle callbacks, or custom prototype methods.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] Its `connectedCallback()` and any other applicable lifecycle callbacks are invoked.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] If the class defines `observedAttributes`, the `attributeChangedCallback()` is called for each attribute that already has a value.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] Normally, elements are upgraded automatically when their definition is registered via `define()`, but only if they are already connected to the document.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry-upgrade] The `upgrade()` method is useful when you need to upgrade elements that exist in a disconnected DOM subtree (for example, elements created via `Document.createElement()` or parsed into a `DocumentFragment`) before they are inserted into the document.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] The **`CustomElementRegistry`** interface provides methods for registering custom elements and querying registered elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] To get an instance of it, use the `window.customElements` property.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] To create a scoped registry, use the `CustomElementRegistry()` constructor.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] Creates a new `CustomElementRegistry` object, for scoped usage.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] Returns the constructor for the named custom element, or `undefined` if the custom element is not defined.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] Returns the name for the already-defined custom element, or `null` if the custom element is not defined.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] Upgrades a custom element directly, even before it is connected to its shadow root.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] Associates a scoped registry with a DOM subtree, setting the custom element registry on each inclusive descendant and upgrading any custom elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] Returns an empty `Promise` that resolves when a custom element becomes defined with the given name.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] If such a custom element is already defined, the returned promise is immediately fulfilled.
[src:custom-elements-deep/customelementregistry] See the Examples section in our guide to using custom elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] In computer science, **reflective programming** or **reflection** is the ability of a process to examine, introspect, and modify its own structure and behavior.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] The earliest computers were programmed in their native assembly languages, which were inherently reflective, as these original architectures could be programmed by defining instructions as data and using self-modifying code.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] As the bulk of programming moved to higher-level compiled languages such as ALGOL, COBOL, Fortran, Pascal, and C, this reflective ability largely disappeared until new programming languages with reflection built into their type systems appeared.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Brian Cantwell Smith's 1982 doctoral dissertation introduced the notion of computational reflection in procedural programming languages and the notion of the meta-circular interpreter as a component of 3-Lisp.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection helps programmers make generic software libraries to display data, process different formats of data, perform serialization and deserialization of data for communication, or do bundling and unbundling of data for containers or bursts of communication.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflective systems may provide a mirror type, used as a decoupled reflection of an object or identifier.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Effective use of reflection almost always requires a plan: A design framework, encoding description, object library, a map of a database or entity relations.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection makes a language more suited to network-oriented code.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] For example, it assists languages such as Java to operate well in networks by enabling libraries for serialization, bundling and varying data formats.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Languages without reflection such as C are required to use auxiliary compilers for tasks like Abstract Syntax Notation to produce code for serialization and bundling.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be used for observing and modifying program execution at runtime.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] A reflection-oriented program component can monitor the execution of an enclosure of code and can modify itself according to a desired goal of that enclosure.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] This is typically accomplished by dynamically assigning program code at runtime.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] In object-oriented programming languages such as Java, reflection allows *inspection* of classes, interfaces, fields and methods at runtime without knowing the names of the interfaces, fields, methods at compile time.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] It also allows *instantiation* of new objects and *invocation* of methods.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is often used as part of software testing, such as for the runtime creation/instantiation of mock objects.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is also a key strategy for metaprogramming.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] In some object-oriented programming languages such as C# and Java, reflection can be used to bypass member accessibility rules.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] For C#-properties this can be achieved by writing directly onto the (usually invisible) backing field of a non-public property.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] It is also possible to find non-public methods of classes and types and manually invoke them.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] This works for project-internal files as well as external libraries such as .NET's assemblies and Java's archives.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] A language that supports reflection provides a number of features available at runtime that would otherwise be difficult to accomplish in a lower-level language.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] These features can be implemented in different ways.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] In MOO, reflection forms a natural part of everyday programming idiom.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] When verbs (methods) are called, various variables such as `verb` (the name of the verb being called) and `this` (the object on which the verb is called) are populated to give the context of the call.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Compiled languages rely on their runtime system to provide information about the source code.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] A compiled Objective-C executable, for example, records the names of all methods in a block of the executable, providing a table to correspond these with the underlying methods (or selectors for these methods) compiled into the program.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] In a compiled language that supports runtime creation of functions, such as Common Lisp, the runtime environment must include a compiler or an interpreter.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be implemented for languages without built-in reflection by using a program transformation system to define automated source-code changes.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection may allow a user to create unexpected control flow paths through an application, potentially bypassing security measures.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Historical vulnerabilities in Java caused by unsafe reflection allowed code retrieved from potentially untrusted remote machines to break out of the Java sandbox security mechanism.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] A large scale study of 120 Java vulnerabilities in 2013 concluded that unsafe reflection is the most common vulnerability in Java, though not the most exploited.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Runtime reflection systems introduce a non-negligible runtime performance overhead.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] For instance, in Java, because reflective operations are resolved dynamically at execution time, many compiler and JVM optimizations—such as method inlining, static binding, and aggressive just-in-time specialization—cannot be fully applied.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] As a consequence, reflective calls are typically slower than their statically resolved counterparts.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] In sequential applications, reflection can significantly increase execution time and memory consumption when used in performance-critical code paths.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] In multithreaded applications, reflective implementations generally preserve scalability, but still exhibit noticeably higher absolute execution times—commonly between 1.5x and 10× slower—than equivalent non-reflective code.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] In languages like C++ and Rust, reflection is performed at compile time.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Compile-time reflection systems are weaker than runtime reflection systems like those of Java and C#, but incur no runtime overhead due to being performed during compilation.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] The following code snippets create an instance `foo` of class `Foo` and invoke its method `PrintHello`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] For each programming language, normal and reflection-based call sequences are shown.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is not possible in C, though parts of reflection can be emulated.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] The following is an example in C++ (using reflection added in C++26).
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Java also provides an internal class (not officially in the Java Class Library) in module `jdk.unsupported`, `sun.reflect.Reflection` which is used by `sun.misc.Unsafe`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] It contains one method, `static Class<?> getCallerClass(int depth)` for obtaining the class making a call at a specified depth.
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] This is now superseded by using the class `java.lang.StackWalker.StackFrame` and its method `Class<?> getDeclaringClass()` .
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] The following is an example in Rust (using procedural macros).
[src:custom-elements-deep/reflection-computer-programming] Swift reflection is read-only, and thus dynamic invocation is only possible through Objective-C.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] One of the key features of web components is the ability to create *custom elements*: that is, HTML elements whose behavior is defined by the web developer, that extend the set of elements available in the browser.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] This article introduces custom elements, and walks through some examples.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] A custom element is implemented as a class which extends `HTMLElement` (in the case of autonomous elements) or the interface you want to customize (in the case of customized built-in elements).
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] This class will not be called by you, but will be called by the browser.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Immediately after defining the class, you should register the custom element, so you can create instances of it using standard DOM practices, such as writing the element in HTML markup, calling `document.createElement()`, etc.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] In the class constructor, you can set up initial state and default values, register event listeners and perhaps create a shadow root.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] At this point, you should not inspect the element's attributes or children, or add new attributes or children.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] See Requirements for custom element constructors and reactions for the complete set of requirements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Once your custom element is registered, the browser will call certain methods of your class when code in the page interacts with your custom element in certain ways.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] By providing an implementation of these methods, which the specification calls *lifecycle callbacks*, you can run code in response to these events.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The position of a custom element in the DOM can be manipulated just like any regular HTML element, but there are lifecycle side-effects to consider.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Each time a custom element is moved (via methods such as `Element.moveBefore()` or `Node.insertBefore()`), the `disconnectedCallback()` and `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callbacks are fired, because the element is disconnected from and reconnected to the DOM.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] However, since these callbacks are typically used to implement any required initialization or cleanup code to run at the start or end of the element's lifecycle, running them when the element is moved (rather than removed or inserted) may cause problems with its state.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] You might for example remove some stored data that the element still needs.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] If you want to preserve the element's state, you can do so by defining a `connectedMoveCallback()` lifecycle callback inside the element class, and then using the `Element.moveBefore()` method to move the element (instead of similar methods such as `Node.insertBefore()`).
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] This causes the `connectedMoveCallback()` to run instead of `connectedCallback()` and `disconnectedCallback()`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] To make a custom element available in a page, call the `define()` method of `Window.customElements`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] This must start with a lowercase letter, contain a hyphen, and satisfy certain other rules listed in the specification's definition of a valid name.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The custom element's constructor function.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Only included for customized built-in elements, this is an object containing a single property `extends`, which is a string naming the built-in element to extend.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Once you've defined and registered a custom element, you can use it in your code.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The examples above register custom elements on the global `CustomElementRegistry` accessed via `Window.customElements`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] This means every custom element name you register must be globally unique across the entire page.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] As applications grow and begin combining components from multiple libraries, global name collisions can become a problem — if two libraries both try to define `<my-button>`, one of them will fail.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] One way to use a scoped registry is to pass it to `Element.attachShadow()` via the `customElementRegistry` option.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] You can also associate a scoped registry after the shadow root has been created by calling `initialize()`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] For declarative shadow DOM, you can use the `shadowrootcustomelementregistry` attribute on a `<template>` element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Like built-in elements, custom elements can use HTML attributes to configure the element's behavior.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] To use attributes effectively, an element has to be able to respond to changes in an attribute's value.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is then called whenever an attribute whose name is listed in the element's `observedAttributes` property is added, modified, removed, or replaced.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Note that if the element's HTML declaration includes an observed attribute, then `attributeChangedCallback()` will be called after the attribute is initialized, when the element's declaration is parsed for the first time.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] For a complete example showing the use of `attributeChangedCallback()`, see Lifecycle callbacks in this page.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Built in HTML elements can have different *states*, such as "hover", "disabled", and "read only".
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Some of these states can be set as attributes using HTML or JavaScript, while others are internal, and cannot.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Whether external or internal, commonly these states have corresponding CSS pseudo-classes that can be used to select and style the element when it is in a particular state.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Autonomous custom elements (but not elements based on built-in elements) also allow you to define states and select against them using the `:state()` pseudo-class function.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The code below shows how this works using the example of an autonomous custom element that has an internal state `"collapsed"`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The `collapsed` state is represented as a boolean property (with setter and getter methods) that is not visible outside of the element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] To make this state selectable in CSS the custom element first calls `HTMLElement.attachInternals()` in its constructor in order to attach an `ElementInternals` object, which in turn provides access to a `CustomStateSet` through the `ElementInternals.states` property.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The setter for the (internal) collapsed state adds the *identifier* `hidden` to the `CustomStateSet` when the state is `true`, and removes it when the state is `false`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The identifier is just a string: in this case we called it `hidden`, but we could have just as easily called it `collapsed`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] We can use the identifier added to the custom element's `CustomStateSet` (`this._internals.states`) for matching the element's custom state.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] This is matched by passing the identifier to the `:state()` pseudo-class.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] For example, below we select on the `hidden` state being true (and hence the element's `collapsed` state) using the `:hidden` selector, and remove the border.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The `:state()` pseudo-class can also be used within the `:host()` pseudo-class function to match a custom state within a custom element's shadow DOM.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Additionally, the `:state()` pseudo-class can be used after the `::part()` pseudo-element to match the shadow parts of a custom element that is in a particular state.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] There are several live examples in `CustomStateSet` showing how this works.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] In the rest of this guide we'll look at a few example custom elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] You can find the source for all these examples, and more, in the web-components-examples repository, and you can see them all live at https://mdn.github.io/web-components-examples/.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] First, we'll look at an autonomous custom element.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The `<popup-info>` custom element takes an image icon and a text string as attributes, and embeds the icon into the page.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] When the icon is focused, it displays the text in a pop up information box to provide further in-context information.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] To begin with, the JavaScript file defines a class called `PopupInfo`, which extends the `HTMLElement` class.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The class definition contains the `constructor()` for the class, which always starts by calling `super()` so that the correct prototype chain is established.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Inside the method `connectedCallback()`, we define all the functionality the element will have when the element is connected to the DOM.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] In this case we attach a shadow root to the custom element, use some DOM manipulation to create the element's internal shadow DOM structure — which is then attached to the shadow root — and finally attach some CSS to the shadow root to style it.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] We don't do this work in the constructor because an element's attributes are unavailable until it is connected to the DOM.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] In the above example we apply styles to the shadow DOM using a `<style>` element, but you can reference an external stylesheet from a `<link>` element instead.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] In this example we'll modify the `<popup-info>` custom element to use an external stylesheet.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] It's just like the original `<popup-info>` example, except that we link to an external stylesheet using a `<link>` element, which we add to the shadow DOM.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Note that `<link>` elements do not block paint of the shadow root, so there may be a flash of unstyled content (FOUC) while the stylesheet loads.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Many modern browsers implement an optimization for `<style>` tags either cloned from a common node or that have identical text, to allow them to share a single backing stylesheet.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] With this optimization the performance of external and internal styles should be similar.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Now let's have a look at a customized built in element example.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] This example extends the built-in `<ul>` element to support expanding and collapsing the list items.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Note that this time we extend `HTMLUListElement`, rather than `HTMLElement`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] This means that we get the default behavior of a list, and only have to implement our own customizations.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] As before, most of the code is in the `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callback.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] You use a `<ul>` element as normal, but specify the name of the custom element inside the `is` attribute.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] So far we've seen only one lifecycle callback in action: `connectedCallback()`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] In the final example, `<custom-square>`, we'll see some of the others.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The `<custom-square>` autonomous custom element draws a square whose size and color are determined by two attributes, named `"size"` and `"color"`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The key function in this example is `updateStyle()` — this takes an element, gets its shadow root, finds its `<style>` element, and adds `width`, `height`, and `background-color` to the style.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The actual updates are all handled by the lifecycle callbacks.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is run whenever one of the element's attributes is changed in some way.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] As you can see from its parameters, it is possible to act on attributes individually, looking at their name, and old and new attribute values.
[src:custom-elements-deep/using-custom-elements] Note that to get the `attributeChangedCallback()` callback to fire when an attribute changes, you have to observe the attributes.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] There are two parts to Custom Elements: autonomous custom elements and customized built-in elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Autonomous custom elements are HTML elements that are entirely separated from native HTML elements; they are essentially built from the bottom up using the Custom Elements API.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Customized built-in elements are elements that are built upon native HTML elements to reuse their functionality.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] The Shadow DOM is a functionality that allows the web browser to render DOM elements without putting them into the main document DOM tree.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] This creates a barrier between what the developer and the browser can reach; the developer cannot access the Shadow DOM in the same way they would with nested elements, while the browser can render and modify that code the same way it would with nested elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] The impact of CSS scoped within the Shadow DOM of a particular element is that HTML elements can be encapsulated without the risk of CSS styles leaking and affecting elements that they were not supposed to affect.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Although these elements are encapsulated with regard to HTML and CSS, they can still fire events that can be picked up by other elements in the document.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] The scoped subtree in an element is called a shadow tree.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] The element the shadow tree is attached to is called a shadow host.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] A Shadow DOM must always be connected to an existing element, either through attaching it as a literal element or through scripting.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] In JavaScript, Shadow DOMs are attached to an element using `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] An HTML template defines a block of HTML content that is not rendered when the page loads, but can be instantiated during runtime.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Scripts within a template do not run, and resources are not fetched, until the content is cloned or added to the DOM.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Web Components are supported by current versions of all major browsers.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Backward compatibility with older browsers is implemented using JavaScript-based polyfills.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] There are many libraries that are built on Web Components with the aim of increasing the level of abstraction when creating custom elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] There are numerous community efforts for the Web Components ecosystem.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] WebComponents.org provides an interface to search for any existing Web Components.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Custom Elements Everywhere validates whether popular front-end frameworks are compatible and ready to use Web Components standard, with a set of pending bugs and available workarounds.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Moreover, Vaadin Tutorials has a dedicated section that shows how those workarounds are used efficiently with example demo apps and similarly related topics.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] In 2011, Web Components were introduced for the first time by Alex Russell at Fronteers Conference.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] In 2013, Polymer, a library based on Web Components was released by Google.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] Polymer is canonical implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] In 2016, RequireJS was introduced as JavaScript library and AMD loader plugin for custom elements.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] In 2017, Ionic (mobile app framework) team built StencilJS, a JavaScript compiler that generates Web Components.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements that lets you package your Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] In 2018, Firefox 63 enabled Web Components support by default and updated the developer tools to support them.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] In 2018, LitElement was developed by the Google Chrome team as part of larger Polymer project.
[src:custom-elements-deep/web-components] LitElement was designed to be a lightweight and easy-to-use framework for creating web components.
